results.notes:
I found this on a tree in Madera Canyon it was really high up on a tree and I cannot remember what kind of tree it was because this was in my beginning years of studying Mushrooms so I had very little knowledge of mushrooms and trees. This Mushroom was about 30 feet high up on a tree. When I looked up from the floor it looked like fomes fomentarius because of the hoof shape. I proceeded to throw a rock at it to knock it down. To my surprise it came off very easily. Upon closer examination I’ve noticed that the pores on this one juUpon closer examination I’ve noticed that the pores on the conk were huge biggest I have ever seen to this day. Approx 2-3mm diameter! It was a type of conk that I have not been able to identify to this day. No expert has been able to identify accurately. Noah Siegel suggested it could be a Inonotus arizonicus. However all of the pictures I have seen don’t match this specimen.
I have gone back to Madera to try and remember what kind of trade this was on but it’s been so long the forest looks so different to me now. I will send this to get it sequenced sometime this year hopefully it’s a new species.

results.notes:
This is a poorly developed pioneering lichen on hard HCL- riverstone on a rocky coastal scrub hillside in northern San Diego.

The thallus is composed of discrete greenish grey areoles on a thin hypothallus of creeping mycelium. The cortex has Norstictic Acid, identified by the presence of red needle-shaped crystals under the cover slip at 400x in KOH.

The apothecia are lecideine, black, plane to convex, epruinose. Epihymenium is dark brown, hymenium is hyaline and not inspersed, hypothecium is dark brown, and the exciple has brown pigments instead of aeruginose pigments. All parts POL-.

Spores are 1-septate, broadly ellipsoid, brown, about 12×6+µm.

This seems to be in the Buellia aethalea group (see Bungartz & Nash 2004), but it lacks aeruginose pigments in the apothecia which seems to be a common feature of this group. The most common coastal species is B. stellulata, but that is K+Y not turning red as it lacks Norstictic Acid. B. spuria is the interior common one with a few coastal records that most closely matches this due to chemistry and spore size. B. aethalea mostly has a hyaline hypothecium. All of these typically have a well developed thallus, but I think this is just extremely immature and not representative of the norm.

results.notes:
Forma típica do que tenho identificado como G. penetrans. Espécie frequente, plástica mas que tende a repetir um padrão:

- Cresce sobre madeira de pinheiro em decomposição (mas que pode estar enterrada).

- Píleo primeiro globoso, depois hemisférico e finalmente aplanado. Cutícula de aparência fibrilosa, mas bem lisa a muito ligeiramente aveludada. Castanha-ferrugem a mais amarelada na margem.

- Himénio adnexo-emarginado. Amarelado-creme a completamente ferruginoso com idade, apesar de manchas ferruginosas aparecerem cedo.

- Estipe esbranquiçado, pruinoso, com restos de véu fugaz que tendem a deixar uma zona anelar (branca ou por vezes ferruginosa pelos esporos) pouco perceptiva no ápice.

-Trama creme a castanha, amarga.

- Esporos elipsoidais-amigdaliformes, verrugosos (ver medidas na imagem).

- Hifas terminais da cutícula tipicamente a rondar os 4-6 micrómetros de diâmetro, não foram encontradas hifas com mais de 10 micrómetros (e muitíssimo raras!). Com óbvio pigmento incrustrado nas paredes, zebrado ou ponteado.

Pode confundir-se mais facilmente com:

- G. hybridus, que tem esporos de menores dimensões (7-7,8 × 4-5 micrómetros) e cortina mais óbvia a formar zona anelar branca, himénio mais adnado-decurrente e cutícula mais tomentosa-fibrilosa (Bon&Roux).
- G. sapineus, que tem cutícula mais fribrilosa-escamosa e respectivas hifas terminais entre 14-18 micrómetros de diâmetro (Bon&Roux).

results.notes:
Fruiting in small groups within boggy area by pine.
Macro:
Pileus around 4 cm broad, brownish-red, lighter towards margin, appressed-fibrillose, becoming somewhat cracked in age, exposing whitish flesh beneath pileipelils; Lamellae whitish, emarginate at stipe, becoming slightly darker in age, eventually dingy brownish, sometimes becoming spotted as well; Stipe about 5 to 6 cm in length and 1 cm thick, firm but becoming hollow, slightly fibrillose, whitish with brownish fibrils; Odor/Taste farinaceous to non-distinct odor, did not taste; Chemical Reactions 10% KOH reddish-violet-burgundy on pileus.
Micro:
Basidiospores elliptical, smooth, irregularly guttulate, hyaline and inamyloid, ~ 6.0 – 6.5 (7.0) x (4.0) 4.2 – 4.8 (5.0) μm; Q = 1.3 – 1.7; N = 22; (95% Conf: L x W = 6.1 – 6.4 × 4.3 – 4.6 μm; Q = 1.38 – 1.45); Basidia clavate, 4-spored; Lamellar trama essentially regular, septate, inflated hyphae present; Pileipellis a cutis, cylindrical hyphal elements; Pileal trama similar to lamellar trama though a bit more ‘irregular’, also more dense than that of lamellar trama; Pleurocystidia absent; Cheilocystidia either absent or non-distinctive, some slender-flexuous cells present on gill edge (~ 15 – 25 × 2 – 4 μm); Clamp connections not found.

results.notes:
Collected on the property of David Lewis.

This collection is a perfect ITS match for what is being called Lactarius quietus var. incanus, and Arleen Basette was calling the same species Lactarius frustratus in New York.

The following Genbank records also refer to this species:

https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/nucleotide/MK578698 USA: New York, Suffolk
https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/nucleotide/MK575245 USA: Indiana, Waveland
https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/nucleotide/DQ424943 USA: Wisconsin, West Salem
https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/nucleotide/MH910574 USA: North Carolina
https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/nucleotide/HE820667 USA: Ohio
https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/nucleotide/KX816125 USA: Mississippi

If the three names are synonymous, the name Lactarius imperceptus takes precedence because it was published in 1940 and the others were published in 1979.   L. imperceptus was described from Florida, and we don’t know what that species really is however.   Microscopy may be able to clarify things here.
